The windy, cloudy day of May of 2008 was the day I was diagnosed with cancer. I was twelve years old. I was at the mall with my mom when she asked me to go get an ice cream. I was happy because I really like ice cream. Then when I was done getting an ice cream, I was just about to go meet my mom, when I felt a little pain in my stomach. I didn't think much of it at the time, but then I started to feel worse and worse. I went to the bathroom to throw up but I couldn't. I thought something must be wrong because I was throwing up, but nothing was coming out. So I went to the ER. They told my mom that I had appendicitis. They took me to get surgery. After the surgery, they told my mom that they had removed my appendix but they had found a tumor that was about the size of my fist. They didn't know what kind of tumor it was or what it was doing in my body. I was scared. I didn't know what was going to happen. I didn't know if I was going to live. I didn't know if I was going to die. But I didn't say anything. I just stared at my mom. I was really scared. They took me to a different hospital. When I got there, they took me to a room. They told my mom that the tumor was cancerous and I needed to have chemo. I was scared. I didn't know what was going to happen. I didn't know if I was going to live. I didn't know if I was going to die. But I didn't say anything. I just stared at my mom. They gave me medicine. I also had an IV in my hand. All of this was new to me. It was all very scary. They also gave me a shot that made me sick. I threw up. Then the next
